02:45.969 --> 02:47.852
He's an amusing man.

02:48.854 --> 02:49.795
Tenant bomb.

02:51.357 --> 02:53.320
Good.

02:53.340 --> 02:53.881
An amusing man.

02:54.101 --> 02:55.203
We were talking on the way over.

02:55.423 --> 02:57.306
If I were to...

02:57.421 --> 03:00.585
to be thinking about this general concept of bibliography.

03:00.605 --> 03:04.329
For instance, I want to talk to Father Boyle at the Vatican Library about the St.

03:04.369 --> 03:08.374
Augustine project, which is supposed to take 400 years or 200 years.

03:10.676 --> 03:13.440
Are you familiar with that project?

03:13.460 --> 03:15.182
I learned about this at the University of Toronto.

03:15.222 --> 03:21.589
I was up at the Fisher Rare Books Library with Richard Landon, and they gave a talk there, and spent three days doing interviews

03:22.058 --> 03:25.262
I'm really excited about that.

03:25.382 --> 03:27.224
It's really going to be very comprehensive.

03:27.905 --> 03:29.587
And they are committed to books.

03:29.627 --> 03:32.470
The British Library is committed to books.

03:33.431 --> 03:39.578
Why is it that we're in such a rush in this country now to slide books out the back door?

03:39.658 --> 03:43.302
I mean, do you see this happening?

03:43.342 --> 03:44.083
Who says that we are?

03:44.671 --> 03:45.192
I'm sorry?

03:45.734 --> 03:46.435
Who says that we are?

03:46.475 --> 03:49.322
Not Harvard, but... In this country.

03:49.924 --> 03:52.670
Well, University of Michigan, for instance.

03:52.690 --> 03:56.299
There's a scandal of the San Francisco Public Library, right?

03:56.319 --> 03:58.023
It's not unique, though.

03:58.043 --> 04:00.148
It's a scandal of the San Francisco Public Library.

04:00.500 --> 04:05.946
Did the library director there win his job at the, what was he up for ALA office?

04:05.986 --> 04:07.367
I don't know, it's July.

04:07.608 --> 04:08.148
Remember that?

04:08.309 --> 04:10.231
Yeah, well, Kenneth Dowland.

04:10.311 --> 04:12.473
In the New York expose?

04:12.613 --> 04:13.714
That's right.

04:13.754 --> 04:17.799
The guy who engineered that was up for a national office.

04:18.159 --> 04:19.260
Ken Dowland is his name.

04:19.280 --> 04:19.441
Really?

04:19.761 --> 04:20.021
Yeah.

04:20.041 --> 04:21.002
I don't know those people.

04:21.363 --> 04:28.971
I don't know who they are and what they do, but that was truly scandalous.

04:28.951 --> 04:33.195
But that's not why he lost his job.

04:35.458 --> 04:37.560
He lost his job because he was spending too much money.

04:37.580 --> 04:38.801
What did he lose his job?

04:38.821 --> 04:39.382
Well, he's out.

04:39.802 --> 04:40.823
Oh, I didn't know that.

04:40.923 --> 04:41.944
He got fired in San Francisco.

04:42.064 --> 04:42.605
Oh, really?

04:42.645 --> 04:45.087
The irony is he's still running for the ALA.

04:45.448 --> 04:47.190
I thought he was going from strength to strength.

04:48.171 --> 04:49.532
No, he's got plastic to fire.

04:49.812 --> 04:52.275
Was there a follow-up to the New Yorker about that?

04:52.715 --> 04:54.557
No, but it was in the San Francisco papers.

04:54.637 --> 04:55.858
I'll happily send you copies.

04:55.878 --> 04:56.379
Oh, no, no, no.

04:56.439 --> 04:57.540
I believe you.

04:57.925 --> 05:01.689
It's just extraordinary because things like that don't happen.

05:01.729 --> 05:11.900
People who do that usually just go on, you know, they're then recruited for the Chicago Public Library, and they become president of IFLA.

05:12.080 --> 05:19.268
Except that the budget was for X millions of dollars, and they're like $130 million in the red.

05:19.468 --> 05:22.031
So it wasn't about what he did.

05:22.091 --> 05:25.314
It had nothing to do with the books.

05:25.715 --> 05:27.797
It had everything to do with the budget.

05:28.199 --> 05:33.604
It's like putting a mafioso in jail for income tax.

05:33.624 --> 05:33.945
Basically, yeah.

05:33.965 --> 05:35.546
Yeah, that's not why he got fired.

05:35.586 --> 05:38.309
He got fired for... Can you bring us two more of these, please?

05:38.329 --> 05:38.629
Sure.

05:40.451 --> 05:41.912
So he got fired for the wrong thing.

05:42.153 --> 05:42.473
Yeah.

05:43.754 --> 05:45.776
I want to send you a... I'm sorry.

05:45.976 --> 05:47.638
I'll mail it out this afternoon.

05:47.658 --> 05:53.264
There's a Pierre Beres piece that was in Le Monde that... Oh, yes, you promised to send me that.

05:53.324 --> 05:53.944
I did, and I'm sorry.

05:53.964 --> 05:54.865
I was going to bring it.

05:55.025 --> 05:56.367
I have just sent him.

05:56.387 --> 05:57.267
Do you read The New Yorker?

05:57.488 --> 05:57.868
I do.

05:58.540 --> 06:00.703
Did you read the issue this week?

06:01.064 --> 06:02.005
My wife has it.

06:02.025 --> 06:03.267
I have it this week.

06:03.287 --> 06:04.189
Look at the cartoons.

06:05.971 --> 06:14.644
You'll find a cartoon done by the guy, I don't know his name, the guy who has kind of shaggy dog people in his cartoons.

06:14.665 --> 06:17.389
Yeah, I know.

06:17.429 --> 06:22.336
And there's this guy standing there wrapped up in a shawl.

06:22.797 --> 06:24.820
Or a, what do you call it?

06:26.683 --> 06:26.843
A shawl.

06:27.110 --> 06:28.011
A cape?

06:28.031 --> 06:28.472
A cape?

06:28.492 --> 06:33.840
No, it's a, I don't know, what do you call it?

06:33.860 --> 06:34.621
Pundled up in the winter.

06:35.462 --> 06:36.423
But a scarf.

06:36.444 --> 06:37.385
A fancy scarf.

06:37.906 --> 06:41.130
Wrapped all around it in several ways, and it's down on the floor.

06:41.531 --> 06:54.670
And the woman who is talking to Samoa, I can mention to the waitress that we want to wear glasses of wine, too.

06:54.690 --> 06:56.813
Is saying,

06:57.316 --> 06:59.802
Oh, I can tell you're a Frenchman from your scarf.

07:02.168 --> 07:13.755
And if you've met Beretz, you know that he has this scarf on always, winter and summer, which he takes from Mallarmé, who had a scarf too.

07:14.528 --> 07:17.192
I saw him at a sale in New York at Sotheby's.

07:17.212 --> 07:18.554
Did he have a scarf?

07:18.574 --> 07:19.756
Yeah, he had a scarf on.

07:20.337 --> 07:21.058
Quite dramatic.

07:21.999 --> 07:26.326
Yes.

07:26.346 --> 07:28.670
Well, who would you recommend?

07:28.690 --> 07:31.774
Now, you say that there are people dying off in Europe.

07:32.175 --> 07:35.320
Who specifically is at the top of your list today?

07:35.340 --> 07:36.582
Who would you urge me to see?

07:36.622 --> 07:40.047
Beres and Lucien Scheler.

07:41.039 --> 07:44.845
Lucien is in Paris, and how do I contact Lucien?

07:45.847 --> 07:49.413
Directly.

07:49.433 --> 07:56.244
He's in the rue de Grinnell, and through Bernard Claveroy, who runs his, who bought his shop.

07:56.264 --> 08:01.292
You remember that Elburn thing?

08:01.525 --> 08:08.293
And I talked about Dilburn going to, went to school with Lucien Shailer, and Shailer made a lot of the quotes about him.

08:13.019 --> 08:16.663
Who is, who brought, who took his shop, who brought his shop again?

08:17.384 --> 08:24.473
Bernard Clavroy, C-L-A-V-R-E-U-I-L.

08:24.593 --> 08:29.139
So what I should do is contact Bernard and ask him if he can put me in touch with Lucien.

08:29.659 --> 08:31.161
Do you have the IFLA directory?

08:31.310 --> 08:32.893
I-F-L-A.

08:33.073 --> 08:33.874
No.

08:34.215 --> 08:36.198
You know what it is?

08:36.238 --> 08:36.479
No.

08:36.859 --> 08:38.462
The International Antiquariat.

08:39.163 --> 08:41.487
No, I don't have that yet.

08:41.507 --> 08:43.751
That's something I should have.

08:43.771 --> 08:46.876
It's full of names and places when you go abroad.

08:47.477 --> 08:50.702
And you can buy it from that...

08:51.340 --> 08:54.708
ABAA Center in Rockefeller?

08:55.048 --> 08:55.369
Really?

08:55.690 --> 08:56.472
Where is it?

08:57.093 --> 08:58.115
I know Leanne.

08:58.135 --> 08:59.819
I'll call Leanne Thomas.

09:00.180 --> 09:10.463
It's very useful and it's got the names of all the dealers so that you would find

09:11.557 --> 09:18.505
an entry for the Lucienne Shaler shop, and you'd find the proprietor as Bernard Cloroyan, I think.

09:18.525 --> 09:21.628
That'd be very useful to you.

09:21.648 --> 09:25.532
They're all worth 25 or 30 bucks, whatever it is.

09:25.572 --> 09:27.554
Do both of these gentlemen speak English, I hope?

09:28.395 --> 09:30.458
Yes, everybody speaks English.

09:30.478 --> 09:37.125
And you and I are the ones that have trouble with it.

09:37.145 --> 09:40.028
Shaler is a, he's an immigrant.

09:40.666 --> 09:42.729
He escaped.

09:43.810 --> 09:45.032
He's a Belgian.

09:46.834 --> 09:50.979
He's very handsome.

09:52.902 --> 09:58.389
I've seen him in the last few years.

09:58.409 --> 10:00.612
He's still very handsome.

10:01.333 --> 10:04.497
And Elbrun

10:04.612 --> 10:06.515
was with Madame Thomas.

10:06.595 --> 10:23.580
He started his own shop.

10:23.700 --> 10:31.211
Manusia came with Madame Thomas.

10:31.231 --> 10:32.433
I think he married her.

10:32.573 --> 10:34.095
He had a child.

10:34.379 --> 10:38.065
He was a bookseller.

10:38.565 --> 10:46.698
And then he had, for the mistress, the child was a bookseller, you said?

10:46.718 --> 10:46.798
Huh?

10:46.818 --> 10:48.681
The child was a bookseller?

10:48.801 --> 10:48.901
Yeah.

10:48.921 --> 10:51.405
He is, I think.

10:52.527 --> 11:00.960
He had as a mistress, um, vial.

11:01.092 --> 11:03.975
I can't do her first name.

11:05.877 --> 11:09.120
Madame Vile, who did the periodical business, is still going in Paris.

11:09.541 --> 11:15.047
So we had these two brilliant booksellers, one for a wife, one for a mistress.

11:16.248 --> 11:17.890
He wrote poetry, published poetry.

11:17.910 --> 11:18.951
Look him up in any catalog.

11:19.131 --> 11:24.957
You find a bunch of poems, and he spells his name S-C-H-E-L-E-R, S-C-H.

11:26.168 --> 11:28.831
And that's how you get Libri Tomas-Shaler.

11:28.851 --> 11:37.642
It'd be wonderful.

11:38.343 --> 11:46.253
What would you love to hear him if you were conducting, if you were me conducting the interview with him, what would you like to hear him talk about?

11:46.233 --> 11:48.339
What would you like to hear him?

11:48.359 --> 11:53.093
I'd like to hear him talk about the occupation.

11:53.214 --> 11:55.520
How'd he get out?

11:55.541 --> 12:00.455
No, he was there the whole time.

12:00.475 --> 12:01.137
He's not Jewish.

12:01.370 --> 12:05.956
He's not Jewish.

12:06.016 --> 12:07.978
No, too bad.

12:08.739 --> 12:10.241
They're not all Jewish, I don't know.

12:10.582 --> 12:12.364
Get me wrong.

12:12.384 --> 12:14.767
They're not Jewish.

12:14.987 --> 12:21.356
But he'd probably tell you about Michel Bernstein, who was Jewish.

12:22.097 --> 12:26.382
So really the idea would be to talk to him about his experiences.

12:26.362 --> 12:35.756
During the occupation, his experiences as a bookseller, his thoughts on, you know, the European attitude.

12:35.837 --> 12:45.612
He was in the Edicione Diminui, which was an attempt by Elouar and others to propagandize through literature.

12:47.675 --> 12:49.658
There were sort of tissue circulation in poems.

12:50.419 --> 12:51.120
I wouldn't believe it.

12:52.248 --> 13:05.802
Typical French idea.

13:06.828 --> 13:10.053
Can you think of some people in Italy, I should say?

13:10.073 --> 13:11.656
No.

13:11.776 --> 13:13.639
No, I don't know them.

13:13.960 --> 13:14.961
How about Otto Schaefer?

13:15.162 --> 13:19.408
Well, that's the interesting other side.

13:19.489 --> 13:22.694
You know, we kept bombing him and bombing him.

13:22.774 --> 13:30.827
I don't think we ever diminished his...

13:30.807 --> 13:33.431
Helpless.

13:33.451 --> 13:38.478
You mean it's a profession?

13:38.679 --> 13:49.114
Because it's making ball bearings through the war.

13:49.134 --> 14:00.190
The story there,

14:00.170 --> 14:04.712
Insurance's use of corporate funds in buying books

14:05.317 --> 14:06.960
The foundation.

14:08.121 --> 14:11.427
And when the economy soured, then he had to sell books.

14:11.447 --> 14:13.450
This is very recent, isn't it?

14:13.570 --> 14:14.772
Yeah.

14:14.872 --> 14:21.423
It's kind of a foundation, is that right?

14:21.623 --> 14:21.883
Mm-hmm.

14:21.943 --> 14:26.571
Had to let his librarian go.

14:26.911 --> 14:32.961
I don't think there'll be any more catalogs like the Incannabula catalog.

14:32.941 --> 14:38.749
And he hasn't been coming to the bibliophiles.

14:39.522 --> 14:49.755
Was he collecting during the war, do you think?

14:50.356 --> 14:52.499
Was he collecting during the war?

14:53.080 --> 15:01.010
I don't know.

15:01.030 --> 15:04.855
The big German officers

15:04.835 --> 15:12.297
We're buying from Paris dealers during the occupation.

15:12.457 --> 15:14.282
Buying legitimately out.

15:14.322 --> 15:20.059
Well, the German citizens were doing out.

15:20.039 --> 15:23.422
Well, I suppose it's all right.

15:24.303 --> 15:28.506
I suppose, I suppose safer might have been.

15:28.526 --> 15:30.788
I don't know.

15:31.269 --> 15:33.911
Interesting question.

15:34.051 --> 15:36.974
But it certainly is the other side, isn't it, as you point out.

15:38.695 --> 15:49.945
Do you have an opinion on how you had said to me before, and without a hint of irony,

15:50.853 --> 15:52.699
that we owe a lot to Hitler.

15:52.720 --> 15:59.985
Of course, you were teasing me and inspiring me to get into this subject, but the trust of what you were saying there

16:00.505 --> 16:16.260
is that because these booksellers came here, because they brought this knowledge, that we, we being the American research fraternity research library, were able to build extraordinary collections.

16:16.501 --> 16:18.343
Could you expand on that?

16:18.383 --> 16:21.706
And you see, at the same time, he destroyed his own book trade.

16:22.507 --> 16:23.768
Hitler did.

16:25.690 --> 16:28.993
So he deprived the German people.

16:29.513 --> 16:32.699
Oh, you know, I was just showing you the Gesamt catalog.

16:34.422 --> 16:38.849
Two weeks ago.

16:40.492 --> 16:41.794
And here it is up to age.

16:41.814 --> 16:45.200
You want me to go?

16:45.982 --> 16:46.422
No.

16:46.563 --> 16:47.364
Age?

16:47.404 --> 16:47.765
Whatever.

16:47.945 --> 16:53.074
And...

16:53.678 --> 17:02.129
I said, until Germany went to war, this was the most advanced work on inkabula in the world.

17:02.189 --> 17:04.391
Really?

17:04.432 --> 17:05.653
What was it again?

17:05.733 --> 17:10.179
Gazamt, G-E-S-A-M-T, you know, okay.

17:10.199 --> 17:10.739
Katalog.

17:10.940 --> 17:16.767
Der Wigendrucker, you know, inkabula.

17:16.747 --> 17:24.582
The Union Catalogue of Incannabula.

17:24.602 --> 17:30.033
It's in the reading room, with all those Incannabula catalogs.

17:30.053 --> 17:36.325
Here's the most advanced work.

17:36.946 --> 17:40.292
But you can't do that sort of thing and make war.

17:40.352 --> 17:44.178
Invasion and this work at home, you can't do all at once.

17:44.339 --> 17:45.080
It's one or the other.

17:45.200 --> 17:56.199
Either you've got to invade other countries and occupy them and that sort of thing, or you've got to leave them alone and take life.

17:57.502 --> 18:02.430
So the thing came to a screeching halt where they began after the war.

18:03.085 --> 18:09.034
And there was some, and to top it off there in the East, you know, instead of the West.

18:09.075 --> 18:12.620
They're situated in East Germany, West Germany.

18:13.662 --> 18:21.955
And now, Lottie Hellinger has got the ISTC going in the British Library.

18:22.306 --> 18:31.098
And she's got the whole alphabet B to Z because she started with Goff R Census in this country.

18:31.118 --> 18:39.048
We let her have the Goff Census keyed in as a basis for the new Incannabular Catalog.

18:39.388 --> 18:41.411
It's online, ISTC.

18:41.511 --> 18:49.782
And the Forges Out Catalog is just out in left field.

18:49.762 --> 18:52.050
In letter H or something like that.

18:52.070 --> 18:54.058
This is like 60 years after the fact.

18:54.540 --> 18:56.346
This is many years after the fact.

18:56.386 --> 18:57.872
Well, you can look at it.

18:57.892 --> 18:59.839
It begins in the 20s, I think.

19:00.292 --> 19:01.454
You know, E.P.

19:01.474 --> 19:04.499
Goldschmidt was a field worker for the Gazam catalog.

19:04.579 --> 19:21.405
And some of those manuscripts of his that you watch sold were field notebooks going to monasteries and town libraries making field notes for the Gazam catalog before he went to England.

19:21.588 --> 19:27.855
And I had a very nice... An excellent interview with Fred Schreiber.

19:27.875 --> 19:31.099
Fred's a little younger, he came here.

19:31.439 --> 19:33.662
Did you get his autobiography?

19:35.284 --> 19:39.469
I have an essay that he wrote about his experience.

19:39.489 --> 19:40.530
Tell me to this country?

19:40.550 --> 19:41.531
Yeah, I do.

19:41.551 --> 19:43.073
I have that.

19:43.390 --> 19:47.278
And then we had lunch in New York a couple months ago.

19:47.298 --> 20:02.428
But he makes the point that what impresses him mostly is the attitude of the European bookseller wants something for this country, not just the ability to buy books and to sell books.

20:02.408 --> 20:04.792
But the scholarship, I guess, I guess they were scholars.

20:05.393 --> 20:06.295
Would you agree with that?

20:06.315 --> 20:07.016
It's a tradition.

20:08.098 --> 20:16.533
It's a European tradition, which they brought here.

20:16.854 --> 20:25.429
I mean, they actually would come to people like Roger Stoddard and say, you have to have these books, and I'm going to tell you why, or I'm going to try and...

20:25.409 --> 20:28.312
Explain to you why I think these books are important.

20:28.332 --> 20:30.874
I mean, is this a simplifying project?

20:30.894 --> 20:32.896
It was a soft sell, though.

20:37.281 --> 20:42.786
Soft with respect to... I don't think any of them said you had to have this book.

20:42.826 --> 20:53.577
Maybe they'd say... I've done some research on this, and this is what I... Over and over again, I say that the Elder Lollier...

20:53.557 --> 21:06.684
He would bring a book to you and he would say, well, I don't know whether this is for you or not or whether you care about it, but maybe it has something for you.

21:06.924 --> 21:13.658
And it would either sell itself to you or it wouldn't.

21:13.638 --> 21:23.156
And you caught on after a while where he knew everything about books, and then he didn't have any books in that shop that weren't worth.

21:23.176 --> 21:26.322
This is the elder lollier.

21:26.342 --> 21:28.846
